European Stocks Are Little Changed Before U.S. Job Data; Fiat Shares Climb

-- B y   W i l l   H a d f i e l d
-- 
2011-06-03T09:35:50Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-03/european-stocks-are-little-changed-before-u-s-job-data-fiat-shares-climb.html
European stocks dropped, with the
benchmark Stoxx Europe 600 Index headed for a fifth week of
declines, as investors awaited a U.S. jobs report that may show
the recovery in the world’s largest economy is faltering. Asian
shares and U.S. futures fell.  Nokia Oyj led technology shares lower, falling 4.8 percent.
Alpha Bank SA and National Bank of  Greece  SA advanced more than
2 percent as investors speculated that the European Union will
bail out the Mediterranean country for a second time. Fiat SpA
rose 3.6 percent as the carmaker buys the rest of the U.S.
government’s stake in Chrysler Group LLC.  The Stoxx 600 lost 0.3 percent to 273.85 at 10:33 a.m. in
 London . European stocks fell to a six-week low yesterday as
Moody’s Investors Service raised Greece’s default risk to 50
percent and a report showed U.S. factory orders dropped more
than forecast in April. Standard & Poor’s 500 Index futures
expiring in June slipped 0.3 percent today, while the MSCI Asia
Pacific Index lost 0.5 percent.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Will Hadfield at 
 whadfield@bloomberg.net  